   BLAST KILLS 47 ON BATTLESHIP IOWA; A fiery explosion in a giant gun turret rocked the refitted battleship Iowa on maneuvers in the Atlantic on 04/19/1989, killing at least 47 sailors and injuring an undetermined number, the Pentagon said. The blast occurred Wednesday, 04/19/1989, morning northeast of Puerto Rico as the Iowa took part in firing exercises that were part of naval training.
  </a>
  <a href="#2" id="2">
   The explosion took place in the No. 2 turret . None of the guns in the no. 2 turret had been fired before the explosion instantly killed the seamen, Navy officials said.
  </a>
  <a href="#3" id="3">
   Eleven men escaped from powder magazines deep within the ship at the base of the turret.
  </a>
  <a href="#4" id="4">
   A dozen crew members suffered minor injuries fighting the fire caused by the explosion.
  </a>
  <a href="#5" id="5">
   Lt. Cmdr. Alan Dooley said a team of six investigators was aboard the ship, searching for clues to the blast . Maj.
  </a>
  <a href="#6" id="6">
   Tom Johnston, a spokesman for the Atlantic Fleet in Norfolk, said he had no information on the causes of death.
  </a>
  <a href="#7" id="7">
   The bodies of 47 sailors killed in the gun explosion on the Iowa arrived in the United States on Thursday, 04/20/1989.
  </a>
